SIMPLE: dame
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dame
<hw>Dame</hw> <pr>(d⟦amac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>dame</ets>, LL. <ets>domna</ets>, fr. L. <ets>domina</ets>
mistress, lady, fem. of <ets>dominus</ets> master, ruler, lord; akin to
<ets>domare</ets> to tame, subdue. See <er>Tame</er>, and cf.
<er>Dam</er> a mother, <er>Dan</er>, <er>Danger</er>, <er>Dungeon</er>,
<er>Dominie</er>, <er>Don</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Duenna</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A mistress of a family, who is a lady; a woman in
authority; especially, a lady.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then shall these lords do vex me half so much,⟦br⟧
As that proud <qex>dame</qex>, the lord protector's wife.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The mistress of a family in common life, or the
mistress of a common school; <as>as, a <ex>dame's</ex>
school</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the <qex>dame's</qex> classes at the village school.</q>
<rj><au>Emerson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A woman in general, esp. an elderly woman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A mother; -- applied to human beings and
quadrupeds.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Damewort</ent>⟦br⟧
